    </lg>
</div>
<div type="koḷu" rend="parallel">
    <p xml:id="TNV17koḷu8">eṉpatu tōḻi talaimakaṉait tuṇintatu.</p>
    </div>
<div type="citation" rend="parallel">
    <lg xml:id="TNV17poem9"> 
        <l>naṇṇuta laritē taṇṇeṉ cāra</l>
        <l>leṇṇiya kuṟaiyoṉ ṟuḷateṉi</l>
        <l>ṉaṇṇātu muṭitti yaṇṇa ṉīyē</l>
    </lg>
</div>
<div type="koḷu" rend="parallel">
    <p xml:id="TNV17koḷu9">eṉpatu talaimakaṉaic cēṭpaṭa niṟuttatu.</p>
    </div>
<div type="citation" rend="parallel">
    <lg xml:id="TNV17poem10"> 
        <l>vāṅkiruñ cilampiṉ vaṇṭa layarun</l>
        <l>tēṅkamaḻ kūntaṉ makaḷiruḷ</l>
        <l>yāṅkā kiyarō<note place="foot"><hi rend="italic">ākiyarō</hi> is relatively common as a rhetorical question in Caṅkam Tamil, employing the optative. cf. KT40. In this case something like 'where will it fall?'. I am non quite sure why UVC felt the need to emend in this case. Perhaps he thought ākiyar was an epicene form and thus corrected it to the neuter singular, though would would be extremely surprising given his breadth of knowledge.</note> vēntaṉiṉ ṉaruḷē</l>
    </lg>
</div>
<div type="koḷu" rend="parallel">
    <p xml:id="TNV17koḷu10">eṉpatu aṟiyāḷ pōṉṟatu.</p>
    </div>
 <div type="citation" rend="parallel">
